  "prompt": "What is act exam?",
  "response": "The ACT (which originally stood for American College Testing) is a standardized test used for college admissions in the United States. It is designed to assess high school students' general educational development and their ability to complete college-level work.\n\nThe test covers four main academic areas:\n\n1. **English**: Tests grammar, punctuation, sentence structure, and rhetorical skills. It consists of 75 questions to be completed in 45 minutes.\n  \n2. **Mathematics**: Covers topics typically learned in courses up to the beginning of 12th grade, including algebra, geometry, and trigonometry. It consists of 60 questions to be completed in 60 minutes.\n\n3. **Reading**: Measures reading comprehension by asking students to read passages and answer questions about them. It consists of 40 questions to be completed in 35 minutes.\n\n4. **Science**: Assesses the interpretation, analysis, evaluation, reasoning, and problem-solving skills required in the natural sciences. It consists of 40 questions to be completed in 35 minutes.\n\nThe ACT also includes an optional **Writing** section, which involves writing an essay in response to a prompt. This section is optional and is 40 minutes long.\n\nEach of the four main sections is scored on a scale of 1 to 36, and the composite score is the average of the four section scores. The writing section is scored separately on a scale of 2 to 12.\n\nThe ACT is widely accepted by colleges and universities in the United States as part of the admissions process, and it is typically taken by high school juniors and seniors. It is offered several times a year at test centers across the country and internationally.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
